Red Wine Quality Exploration by Nan Li

This report explores the dataset contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine.

Alcohol - Count plot

Alcohol - Count plot by log10 x-axis

As we knew, long tail is suit for log10. It’s better to understand the distribution of alcohol. The transformed alcohol distribution appears bimodal with the peaking around 9.25 and 9.8. But there is a gap at 9.5. The reason is no red wine is between 9.45 and 9.5.

Alcohol - Count plot for each quality

From above figure, I can tell the higher alcohol content means the higher quality wine.

Fixed.acidity and Volatile.acidity - Count plot for each quality

If volatile acidity is too high, it will degrade the quality of red wine due to the vinegar taste. There is no any value over 1 in higher quality 7 and 8.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

In this red wine dataset, there are totally 1599 red wines with 11 input attributes(physicochemical) and 1 output attribute(quality). For quality, the range of score is from 0 to 10. 0 is the worst quality and 10 is the best quality.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features are quality, alcohol, fixed and volatile acidity, critric acid, free and total sulfur dioxide.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

From most results, it’s hard to make a conclude which one feature strongly effect the quality of red wine. I also think residual sugar and chlorides will effect the taste of the red wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created two new variables, one is the ratio between fixed and volatile acidity and the other one is bound sulfur dioxide which equals total minus free sulfur dioxide.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

First, I removed the x column which is index. For some features, I log-transformed the right skewed distributions.I found many 0 values in the citric acid feature and those are all missing values.So I decided to delete them and draw the graph.

Top 4 correlation coefficients with quality are:

alcohol = 0.4762, volatile.acidity = -0.3906, sulphates = 0.2514, citric.acid = 0.2263.

The quality does not strongly correlate with any other variables. The highest correlation coefficient is 0.4762 with alcohol. So the alcohol content can decide the quality. On the other hand, the more volatile.acidity, the worse quality.

Top 4 correlation coefficients in datas are:

fixed.acidity with pH = -0.6830, fixed.acidity with citric.acid = 0.6717, fixed.acidity with density = 0.6680, total.sulfur.dioxide with free.sulfur.dioxide = 0.6677.

In addition, since total.sulfur.dioxide is including free.sulfur.dioxide, they tend to correlate with each other. And fixed.acidity has a negitive coefficient with PH due to the acid. Consider the figures below.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

The sulphate and alcohol contents are very important for the quality of redwine, expecially higher quality levels such as 7 and 8.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

For other features, it looks like fixed.acidity strongly correlated with some features. It negatively correlated with pH because the acid leads to a lower pH. And it also positive correlated with citric.acid and density.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship was between fixed.acidity and pH, which had a correlation coefficient of -0.6830.

Description One

It shows the best redwine has a highest alcohol content. So when we find some higher alcohol content in the redwine, it deserves to be paied.

Plot Two

Description Two

The trend of this figure is the higher quality is on the top right and the lower quality is on the bottom left. It’s easy to conclude the alcohol and sulphates are positively correlated with quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

The prediction of the quality by linear model is obviously smaller than the real quality. It reflects the linear model is not suitable for this dataset. ——

Reflection

The red wine quality dataset contains 1599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. In order to explore the chemical properties influence the quality, I tried to describe one variable, two variables and multiple variables by drawing the plots. Such as the volatile acidity negatively correlated to quality. A large amount of volatile acidity can lead to an unpleasant vinegar taste. However, the citric acid and sulphates can improve the quality since citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines and sulphates can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas levels. I also created a linear model and tried to predict the quality. The predict quality is lower than the real quality.

For data exploration, I’m thinking whether the number of dataset is a little bit small and it is not fair enough since only three experts graded the red wine. Maybe we can find 10 more experts to evaluate the red wine.

From the beginning to the end, I created so many plots. It is hard to tell which one is representative. So I wrote some comments after each plot and it will make easier to decide which one I should put in the conclusion.

For future work, I will try other model to predict the quality and compare with the linear model.
